                    </div>
                    <span>I have come late to this book so have little much to add to what other reviewers have stated except to observe that why this book is such a thought provoking and enjoyable read for me (despite in several areas covering concepts that probably mean little in isolation) is due to:
<br />
<br />1. Gladwell's wide ranging and excellent choice of examples that serve to support his messages (a book that can range from why Paul Revere's ride was so effective to the simple initial steps that were critical to reducing the NY crime wave of 1980s is bound to provoke interest);
<br />
<br />2. In developing his key themes Gladwell presents his case with the making of several key "connections" to produce a very convincing case;and,
<br />
<br />3. Finally, he covers a very challenging issue of how to stop (or at least reduce) people smoking as a test of his case.
<br />
<br />A very provoking book of ideas and concepts which given I am currently involved in a major project which involves how to better develop and produce information which will have greater "stickiness" and change people's views and approach has come at just the right time!</span>
                  
